In [[Jainism]], '''Puṣpadanta''' ({{lang-sa|पुष्पदन्त}}), also known as '''Suvidhinatha''', was the ninth [[Tirthankara]] of the present age (''[[Avasarpini]]''). According to Jain belief, he became a [[siddha]] and an [[arihant (Jainism)|arihant]], a liberated soul that has destroyed all of its [[Karma in Jainism|karma]].

==Biography==
Puṣpadanta, also known as Suvidhinatha, was the ninth [[Tirthankara]] of the present age (''[[Avasarpini]]'').{{sfn|Tukol|1980|p=31}} According to Jain belief, he became a [[siddha]] and an [[arihant (Jainism)|arihant]], a liberated soul that has destroyed all of its [[Karma in Jainism|karma]].{{cn|date=June 2016}}

Puṣpadanta was born to King Sugriva and Queen Rama at Kakandi (modern Khukhundoo, [[Deoria, Uttar Pradesh]]) to the [[Ikshvaku dynasty]].{{sfn|Tukol|1980|p=31}} His birth date was the fifth day of the Margshrsha Krishna month of the [[Vikram Samvat]]. Puṣpadanta was the ninth Tirthankara who re-established [[Jain monasticism|the four-part sangha]] in the tradition started by [[Rishabhanatha]]. Pushpadanta is associated with Alligator emblem, Malli tree, Ajita [[Yaksha]] and Mahakali (Dig.) & Sutaraka (Svet.) [[Yakshi]].{{sfn|Tandon|2002|p=44}}

