'''Ruth Padilla DeBorst''' is a [[Latin American]] [[evangelical]] [[theology|theologian]] affiliated with the [[Latin American Theological Fellowship]] and based in [[Costa Rica]].
== Biography == Padilla DeBorst was born in [[Colombia]] as the eldest daughter of an American mother, Catharine Feser Padilla,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0w-vCwAAQBAJ|title=Mission as Transformation: Learning from Catalysts|last=Padilla DeBorst|first=Ruth|publisher=Wipf & Stock|year=2013|isbn=978-1-62564-612-5|editor=David Cranston|location=Eugene, OR|pages=33–38|chapter=Catharine Feser Padilla|editor2=Ruth Padilla DeBorst}}</ref> and an [[Ecuador]]ian father, the theologian [[René Padilla]]. She attended high school and university in [[Argentina]], receiving her [[B.Ed.]] at the [[Instituto Nacional Superior en Lenguas Vivas]] in 1984, an [[M.A.]] in [[Interdisciplinary Studies]] at [[Wheaton College (Illinois)|Wheaton College]] in 1987, and a [[PhD]] in theology from [[Boston University]] in 2016, under the supervision of [[Dana L. Robert]].<ref name="ct">{{cite journal|last1=Crouch|first1=Andy|date=August 2007|title=Liberate My People|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2007/august/12.30.html|journal=Christianity Today|volume=51|issue=8|pages=30–33|via=}}</ref><ref name="phd">{{cite thesis |type=PhD |last=Padilla DeBorst |first=Ruth Irene |date=2016 |title=Integral mission formation in Abya Yala (Latin America): A study of the ''Centro de Estudios Teológicos Interdisciplinarios'' (1982-2002) and radical Evangélicos |publisher=Boston University| url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/1832022854}}</ref> She is known for being an advocate of [[integral mission]], an evangelical form of [[liberation theology]].<ref name="phd"/>
She is a former president of the [[Latin American Theological Fellowship]] (known in Spanish as Fraternidad Teológica Latinoamericana or FTL) and continues to serve on their board. She was a keynote speaker at the evangelical conference [[Lausanne Committee for World Evangelization|Lausanne 2010]], held in [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]].<ref name="ct"/>
Her first husband was killed in Ecuador when she was eight months pregnant and with two small children.<ref>{{cite news|title=My husband's murder deepened my faith|url=https://www.christiantoday.com/article/my-husbands-murder-deepened-my-faith/39084.htm|accessdate=5 January 2018|publisher=Christian Today|language=en}}</ref> She currently lives with her second husband, James Padilla DeBorst, in [[San José, Costa Rica]], and they together lead the Comunidad de Estudios Teológicos Interdisciplinarios.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth Padilla DeBorst|url=http://www.missioalliance.org/author/rpadilladeborst/|website=Missio Alliance|accessdate=5 January 2018}}</ref>
