{{distinguish|Zechariah Mendel ben Aryeh Leib of Cracow}}
'''Zechariah Mendel ben Aryeh Leib''' (died 1791) ([[Hebrew]]: '''זכריה מנדל בן אריה ליב''') was a [[Galician Jews|Galician]] and [[History of the Jews in Germany|German]] preacher and scholar born at [[Podhaice]] in the early part of the 18th century. He died at [[Frankfurt (Oder)|Frankfurt-on-the-Oder]] on December 20, 1791.

He was of the same family as [[Solomon Luria]] and [[Moses Isserles]], who traced their genealogy to [[Rashi]]. Zechariah Mendel's principal teacher was [[Jacob Joshua]], author of ''Pene Yehoshua''. Zechariah Mendel was preacher in the [[Talmud Torah]] at Frankfurt-on-the-Oder. He left many writings, of which only the following three have been published (at Frankfort-on-the-Oder):
* ''Menorat Zekaryah'' (1776), a work containing novellæ on the tractate [[Moed|Shabbat]] and homilies for the [[Shabbat|Sabbath]] and holy days
* ''Zekaryah Meshullam'' (1779), a sequel to the preceding work, and containing novellæ on the [[Talmud]]
* ''Zekaryah ha-Mebin'' (1791), a guide to religious philosophy and to the knowledge of the true [[Kabbalah|Kabala]].

